Two-Sample Hypothesis Test for Proportions

An online men’s clothing retailer has developed a testing framework for video advertising on YouTube in order to test the effectiveness of the ads on influencing individuals to purchase from their website.

Over the course of 30 days, 600,000 consumers were reached on YouTube. Half of the individuals reached with ads on YouTube were served Public Service Announcement ads, while the other half were served ads for the retailer.

Incrementality testing, also referred to as “Uplift Modeling” or “Incremental Sales Lift”, is a test that measures the impact of a single variable on an individual’s behavior. For digital display or video marketing, it is most commonly used to measure the impact of a branded digital ad (Test Group) against a Public Service Announcement (PSA) ad (Control Group). The lift is measured as the percent difference between the two.

Incremental lift indicates the impact of a particular (digital) advertising tactic on sales – the holy grail of advertising. It is possible to calculate but incremental testing is expensive (budget must still be spent on PSA placebo ads) and subject to many pitfalls unless executed carefully. For the purposes of this assignment we will assume that all individuals were not exposed to any other advertising for the retailer during the 30 day testing period.

The goal of our test is to determine whether the conversion rate of the test group is different than the conversion rate of our control group. Conversion rate in this case is defined as \[\textrm{Conversion Rate} = \Bigg(\frac{ \textrm{Individuals in Group Who Purchased}}{\textrm{Total Individuals in Group}}\Bigg)\]

Our hypothesis will test whether the difference in conversion rate or proportion for the test group and control group is statistically significant when \(\alpha\) = 0.01.\[H_0 : p_{test} - p_{control} = 0\] \[H_a : p_{test} - p_{control} \neq 0\]

The data we will be using for the following exercises is test_control.csv. This data represents a simple random sample of 15,000 individuals served PSA ads and 15,000 individuals served a branded digital video ads. The data also contains an indicator for whether an individual purchased from our retailer after viewing the ad.

Hypothesis Test

  1. What is the difference in the conversion rate for the test and control groups?
# Taking the differnce between conversion rates which were calculated earlier.
conv_diff <- exp_conv-control_conv
conv_diff
## [1] 0.004

The confidence interval for the difference between two proportions (when n > 30) is defined as \[p_{test} - p_{control} \pm z_{\alpha/2}\sqrt{\frac{p_{test} \times (1-p_{test})}{n_{test}}+ \frac{p_{control} \times (1-p_{control})}{n_{control}} }\]

  1. Using the equation above, write a function to calculate the confidence interval for the difference between two proportions. Your function should include three arguments: p1, p2, n1, n2 and Z. Your function should return the confidence interval for the difference in two proportions at a given confidence level (in our example, Z = 2.575 when \(\alpha\) = 0.01) Round your results to the first five decimal places.
# Creating confidence interval function using the provided equation
confidence <- function(p1, p2, n1, n2, z){
  # Finding the lower confidence interval based on the given equation
  lower_confidence_interval <- p1-p2-(z*(sqrt((p1*(1-p1)/n1) + (p2*(1-p2)/n2))))
  # Finding the upper confidence interval based on the given equation
  upper_confidence_interval <- p1-p2+(z*(sqrt((p1*(1-p1)/n1) + (p2*(1-p2)/n2))))
  # Creating vector for both confidence intervals, with 5 decimal places
  confidence_interval <- round(c(lower_confidence_interval, upper_confidence_interval), digits = 5)
  return(confidence_interval)
}
  1. Calculate the confidence interval for the difference between the conversion rates for our test and control groups when \(\alpha\) = 0.01 (Z = 2.575) using your function. Does this confidence interval include zero? What are the implications for the difference between two means when the confidence interval does not include zero?
#Calling our function using the number of exposed and control, and z value of 2.575
confidence(exp_conv, control_conv, 15000, 15000, 2.575)
## [1] 0.00103 0.00697

No, this interval does not include 0. A confidence interval for a two sided hypothesis that does not include zero would imply that there is indeed a significant difference between two proportions or conversion rates. This confident interval suggests that given the 99% confidence level, the difference between the means for each proportion should not be equal to zero, which will allow the null hypothesis to be rejected.

  1. Similar to the t.test() function in R, the prop.test() function can be used for testing the null hypothesis that the proportions (probabilities of success) in several groups are the same, or that they equal certain given values. A chi-square test for equality of two proportions is exactly the same test as a z-test (chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom is just that of a normal deviate, squared). What are the arguments for the function prop.test()?
?prop.test

The arguments of prop.test() are: [x] - X is the vector of how many successes from our data. Can also be a table. [n] - N is the vector with how many trials are in our data. [p] - The probabilities of success. Defaults to null. [alternative] - Either two sided, greater or less. Tests to see if the proportions are equal or if one proportion equals a value. [conf.level] - Specifies the confidence level of the confidence interval. [correct] - Whether or not to apply the Yates continuity correction.

  1. Noting that the arguments x and n require vectors of values, use the prop.test() function to test our hypothesis that there is a statistically significant difference between the conversion rates of our test and control groups.
# Calling the prop test function with the number of users who purchased in both groups.
# Also using the number of users in each group (15000), the two sided test, with a confidence interval and the Yates correction applied.
prop.test(c(181, 121), c(15000, 15000), alternative = 'two.sided', conf.level = 0.99, correct = FALSE)
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity
##  correction
## 
## data:  c(181, 121) out of c(15000, 15000)
## X-squared = 12.042, df = 1, p-value = 0.0005202
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 99 percent confidence interval:
##  0.001031445 0.006968555
## sample estimates:
##      prop 1      prop 2 
## 0.012066667 0.008066667
  1. Interpet each output of prop.test. Explain your p-value in the context of our hypothesis. Is the difference in the conversion rates for the test and control groups statistically significant?

Our null hypothesis for this data is there theres is no difference between the conversion rates of both the control and exposed groups. Given that we are using a two-sided test, we are looking to see that there is any difference between the two, whether one is higher or lower than the other. Prop.test provides a p value of 0.0005, which suggests that there is a very small chance that there is no difference between the two proportions, and the null hypothesis can be rejected.

  1. Use the function pchisq(x, df=1) to try to understand the X-squared score value in the output of prop.test(). What do the “p” functions for distributions calculate in R? Subtract the value calculated using pchisq from 1. What does this value represent?
pchisq(12.042, df=1)
## [1] 0.9994798
?pchisq
1 - pchisq(12.042, df=1)
## [1] 0.0005201513

The p functions for distributions calculate the probability of a random variable being less than or equal to one possible outcome in the sample space, i.e. the cumulative distribution function. The value calculated from pchisq is the probability that our two proportions are different from one another. Subtracting this value from one provides us a p value, which suggests whether or not the null hypothesis that there is no difference between the two proportions can be rejected.

Conclusion

  1. In a few sentences, describe your interpretation of the results we found in this assignment. How might the demographic data we observed for our test and control groups impact the difference in the two conversion rates? Do you still believe that the results of our hypothesis test is valid? Justify your answer.

We found in this assignment that ads may have been effective in driving more exposed users to transact compared to control users. There was a statistically significant difference between the two groups based on our testing the proportions of both groups. However, our results may have been influenced by the demographics between the two groups. Since the exposed group contained older users with higher incomes, they may have been more likely to purchase, without the influence of ads. However, this may work in the opposite direction depending on the targets of the campaign. If the product was actually designed for younger audiences, the older skew of the exposed group may have worked against it, and may have led to fewer purchases than what would have been possible with a more even age distribution. I believe that this test is still valid for that very reason - based on statistics alone, the exposed group “performed” better. Without additional outside information that may lend more insight into the demographics and the ads themselves, it would be difficult to say that the results are invalid.
